{
  "answer": "**The *Kalpabuddha* (by Unknown, work slug `unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc`), Chapter 6.**\n\nThe text describes returning the Lord Pañcatathāgata to their `lokadhātu`s and reinstalling them in the body as the five wisdoms (`pañcajñāna`), equated with the five senses (`pañcendriya`): eyes (`cakṣus`), ears (`śrotra`), nose (`ghrāṇa`), mouth (`jihvā`), and heart/liver (`hṛdaya`). It then maps them as follows:\n\n> Now, as for the deities of the five senses: **Lord Akṣobhya resides in the eyes, Lord Ratnasambhava resides in the ears, Lord Amitābha resides in the nose, Lord Amoghasiddhi resides in the mouth. He who is the sense of taste is Lord Vairocana, residing in the heart, he is the mind.** There also are their respective `devī`s. **That is what is called the Divine Five-Souls (`Pañcātma`), which form the self.**[^1]\n\n[^1]: *Kalpabuddha*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-kalpabuddha-d760dc/06/translation/#p-c8567e).",
